<subSubSection pageId="91" pageNumber="369" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="369" targetBox="[742,746,2115,2136]" targetPageId="91">
<paragraph blockId="91.[738,1331,1164,1586]" pageId="91" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[739,922,1356,1389]" pageId="91" pageNumber="369">Distribution.</emphasis>
NC Costa Rica to WC Panama.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="91" pageNumber="369" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="91.[738,1331,1164,1586]" pageId="91" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[739,988,1435,1468]" pageId="91" pageNumber="369">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 89-93 mm, tail 119-145 mm, ear 13-17 mm, hindfoot 22-25 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Talamancan Harvest
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="91.[122,1328,1592,2136]" pageId="91" pageNumber="369">
Mouse is the largest species of 
<taxonomicName box="[578,786,1592,1625]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Reithrodontomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="91" pageNumber="369" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Reithrodontomys</taxonomicName>
. Dorsum is brownish orange, infused with black guard hairs; sides are tawny; and venter is pinkish cinnamon. Compared to the Narrow-nosed Harvest Mouse (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1901" box="[617,804,1675,1704]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Reithrodontomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="91" pageNumber="369" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tenuirostris">R. tenuirostris</taxonomicName>
), the Talamancan Harvest Mouse has larger skull and more robust rostrum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="91" pageNumber="369" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="91.[122,1328,1592,2136]" pageId="91" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[124,235,1749,1782]" pageId="91" pageNumber="369">Habitat.</emphasis>
Wet forested areas with grasses and fallen logs and bases of rock cliffs generally above elevations of 2290 m. The Talamancan Harvest Mouse is found throughout high-elevation regions of south-central Costa Rica and west-central Panama, especially at various volcanoes and throughout the 
<taxonomicName authority="de Talamanca." box="[701,1054,1867,1900]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chrysobalanaceae" genus="Cordillera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="91" pageNumber="369" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Cordillera de Talamanca.</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
